aesi.io
Class IO

java.lang.Object
  aesi.io.IO
Direct Known Subclasses:
StateWriter
public class IO
extends java.lang.Object

A class that contains a lot of public static functions to manipulate data on the computer. These functions will probably always come in handy as now a simple actions such a writing to a file can be performed in one line of code with a simple boolean indicating success without the pain of having to add try-catch statements or considering thousands of scenarios for what could be the case, i.e.: does the file exist? do I have write access?

Also, this class only contains static methods but Java does not support the static declaration for classes. The result is a disappointing constructor entry in the JavaDoc. We should sincerely consider compiling this JavaDoc from source for the full effect. For now, please ignore the constructor entry in the JavaDoc, it's not supposed to be there!

Method Detail

writeFile

public static boolean writeFile(java.lang.String fileName,
                                java.lang.String content)
Writes the String content to the file represented by fileName. Actually uses the other writeFile method where it matches the arguments and fills in overwrite as false.

  • If the file already exists the existing file is updated.
  • If the file does not yet exist the file is created.
  • If anything fails an error is printed to System.err in the format ERROR: error message.

    Parameters:
    fileName - The string that represents a file.
    content - The string that represents the content that will be written in the file.
    Returns:
    A boolean indicating success. If anything fails this boolean is false, otherwise true.
    See Also:
    updateFile(File file, String content), writeFile(String fileName, String content, boolean overwrite)

    • writeFile

    public static boolean writeFile(java.lang.String fileName,
                                java.lang.String content,
                                boolean overwrite)
    Writes the String content to the file represented by fileName, overwrites when overwrite is true and updates the said file when false.

  • If the file already exists and overwrite is true the existing file is deleted and a new found created with content as the content.
  • If the file already exists and overwrite is false the existing file is updated.
  • If the file does not yet exist the file is created.
  • If anything fails an error is printed to System.err in the format ERROR: error message.

    Parameters:
    fileName - The string that represents a file.
    content - The string that represents the content that will be written in the file.
    overwrite - The boolean that indicates if the file should be updated or deleted when the file already is in existence.
    Returns:
    A boolean indicating success. If anything fails this boolean is false, otherwise true.
    See Also:
    updateFile(File file, String content), writeFile(String fileName, String content)

    • updateFile

    public static boolean updateFile(java.io.File file,
                                 java.lang.String content)
    Updates a file object with content which will be written at the end of the file. This method uses a BufferedWriter and I have a feeling this is quite optimal!

    This file is probably mostly called by writeFile(String fileName, String content, boolean overwrite).

    If anything goes south an error is printed to System.err in the format ERROR: error message.

    Parameters:
    file - The File object representing the file to be updated.
    content - The content, a string to be added (written) on the bottom of the file.
    Returns:
    A boolean indicating success. If anything fails this boolean is false, otherwise true.
    See Also:
    writeFile(String fileName, String content, boolean overwrite)

    deleteFile

    public static boolean deleteFile(java.lang.String fileName)
    Deletes a file. Not everything is completely implemented. The result of this is clear when runtime errors are thrown. Preferably I would like to see indications of success or failure only in the returned boolean.

    Parameters:
    fileName - The string that represents the file that needs to be deleted
    Returns:
    A boolean indicating success. If anything fails this boolean is false, otherwise true. This does not mean that when false is returned the file is not there, it could also mean the file did not exist in the first place.

    readFileAsLines

    public static java.lang.String[] readFileAsLines(java.lang.String file)
    Reads a file as a string array. If anything fails an error is printed to System.err in the format ERROR: error message. This method is current also used by readFile(String), which, inefficiently, reads a file as a string.

    Parameters:
    file - A string that represents the file to be read.
    Returns:
    A string array that is the content of the file or null when something went wrong.
    See Also:
    readFile(String)

    readFile

    public static java.lang.String readFile(java.lang.String file)
    Reads a file as a string. If anything fails an error is printed to System.err in the format ERROR: error message. This method is currently very Lazily implemented and actually uses readFileAsLines(String file) to first create a string array which it then converts to a string using an enhanced for loop.

    Parameters:
    file - A string that represents the file to be read.
    Returns:
    A string that is the content of the file or null when something went wrong.
    See Also:
    readFileAsLines(String file)
